            <fr:route>jms-017L.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Deterministic finite automaton">Deterministic finite automaton</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>deterministic finite automaton</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>DFA</fr:strong></fr:em> for short is an <fr:link href="jms-017H.xml" title="Non-deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017H" type="local">NFA</fr:link> for which the transition relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta \colon  Q\times  \Sigma \mathbin {\nrightarrow } Q]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>, i.e. a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">total</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link> relation. This states, in other words, that to each state each state <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  Q]]></fr:tex> can transition along each symbol <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \Sigma ]]></fr:tex> to one and only one state, which we conventionally write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta {\mathopen {}\left (q,a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Indeed, we will often write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M = (Q,\Sigma ,\delta ,s,F)]]></fr:tex> for a DFA. In this case, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \mathrel {\xrightarrow {a}}q']]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta {\mathopen {}\left (q,a\right )\mathclose {}}=q']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
